---
import BlogLayout from '../../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
const faq = [
  { q: `Is Bopomofo only used in Taiwan?`, a: `Yes, Zhuyin (Bopomofo) is primarily used in Taiwan. It is the standard phonetic system taught in Taiwanese schools and used on most Taiwanese keyboards and children's books. Mainland China, Singapore, Malaysia, and most international Chinese programs use Pinyin instead.` },
  { q: `Can I learn both Pinyin and Bopomofo?`, a: `Absolutely. Since both systems represent exactly the same sounds, learning one makes the other much easier. Many students start with Pinyin (as it uses familiar Latin letters) and add Zhuyin later if they plan to study or live in Taiwan. The transition typically takes 1-2 weeks.` },
  { q: `Which system is better for learning Chinese?`, a: `Neither is objectively better — they are tools for the same job. Pinyin has the advantage of using letters you already know. Bopomofo has the advantage of preventing English pronunciation interference. Your choice should depend on your learning context, teacher, and where you plan to use Chinese.` },
  { q: `Will I be confused using Pinyin in Taiwan?`, a: `Not really. Most Taiwanese people understand Pinyin even though they grew up with Zhuyin. Street signs and MRT stations in Taiwan often show Pinyin romanization. However, Taiwanese keyboards, children's books, and dictionary apps primarily use Zhuyin.` },
  { q: `How long does it take to learn Bopomofo if I already know Pinyin?`, a: `About 1-2 weeks for the symbols, then another 2-3 weeks to reach comfortable reading speed. The sounds are identical — you only need to learn the new visual symbols. Daily practice with flashcards and our Zhuyin Converter tool speeds up the process.` }
];
const relatedTools = [
  { name: "Zhuyin Converter", url: "/chinese/tools/zhuyin-converter/" },
  { name: "Pinyin Converter", url: "/chinese/tools/pinyin-converter/" },
  { name: "Tone Trainer", url: "/chinese/tools/tone-trainer/" }
];
const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: "what-are-they", text: "What Are Pinyin and Bopomofo?" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "history", text: "A Brief History of Both Systems" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "side-by-side", text: "Side-by-Side Symbol Comparison" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "pinyin-pros-cons", text: "Pinyin: Advantages and Disadvantages" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "bopomofo-pros-cons", text: "Bopomofo: Advantages and Disadvantages" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "decision-guide", text: "Which Should You Learn? Decision Guide" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "learning-both", text: "Learning Both: The Best Approach" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "typing-input", text: "Typing and Input Methods" }
];
---
<BlogLayout
  title="Bopomofo vs Pinyin: Complete Comparison Guide for Chinese Learners"
  description="Compare Zhuyin (Bopomofo) and Pinyin side by side: symbols, advantages, disadvantages, and a decision guide for which pronunciation system to learn based on your goals."
  language="chinese"
  category="chinese-basics"
  tags={["zhuyin", "bopomofo", "pinyin", "taiwan", "pronunciation", "beginner"]}
  publishDate="2026-02-18"
  image="https://images.pexels.com/photos/36001568/pexels-photo-36001568.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&dpr=2&h=650&w=940"
  imageAlt="A mother helps her baby stand near a colorful pavilion in a park setting."
  faq={faq}
  relatedTools={relatedTools}
  headings={headings}
>

  <div class="prose max-w-none">

    <p>If you are starting to learn Chinese, one of your first decisions is which phonetic system to use: <strong>Pinyin</strong> (the Latin-letter system used worldwide) or <strong>Bopomofo</strong> (the unique symbol system used in Taiwan, also called Zhuyin Fuhao 注音符號). Both systems do the exact same thing — represent the pronunciation of Chinese characters — but they look completely different and are used in different contexts.</p>

    <p>This guide gives you a thorough, unbiased comparison so you can make the right choice for <strong>your</strong> situation. We will cover the history, symbols, advantages, disadvantages, and practical typing considerations for each system.</p>

    <!-- What Are They -->

    <div style="margin: 2rem 0; padding: 1.2rem; background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2, #eff6ff); border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #e5e7eb; text-align: center;"><div style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">📖</div><div style="font-weight: 700; color: #111827; font-size: 1rem;">Bopomofo Vs Pinyin</div><div style="color: #6b7280; font-size: 0.8rem; margin-top: 0.3rem;">Complete Learning Guide</div></div>

    <h2 id="what-are-they">What Are Pinyin and Bopomofo?</h2>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <div style="background: #eff6ff; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
        <h3 style="margin: 0 0 0.8rem; color: #2563eb;">📝 Pinyin (拼音)</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; margin: 0 0 0.8rem;">Uses <strong>Latin letters</strong> with tone marks to represent Chinese pronunciation.</p>
        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; text-align: center; font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
          nǐ hǎo
        </div>
        <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2rem;">
          <li>Developed in 1950s, mainland China</li>
          <li>International ISO standard since 1982</li>
          <li>Used by most Chinese textbooks worldwide</li>
          <li>Default on smartphones and computers globally</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div style="background: #fef3c7; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
        <h3 style="margin: 0 0 0.8rem; color: #ca8a04;">🔣 Bopomofo / Zhuyin (注音符號)</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; margin: 0 0 0.8rem;">Uses <strong>unique phonetic symbols</strong> derived from Chinese characters to represent pronunciation.</p>
        <div style="background: white; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1rem; text-align: center; font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
          ㄋㄧˇ ㄏㄠˇ
        </div>
        <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2rem;">
          <li>Created in 1913, Republic of China era</li>
          <li>Standard system in Taiwan</li>
          <li>Used in Taiwanese schools and children's books</li>
          <li>Primary keyboard input in Taiwan</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The critical thing to understand: <strong>both systems represent the exact same sounds</strong>. Every sound you can write in Pinyin has a Zhuyin equivalent, and vice versa. The difference is purely in the visual symbols used. Try converting between them with our <a href="/chinese/tools/zhuyin-converter/">Zhuyin Converter</a>.</p>

    <!-- History -->
    <h2 id="history">A Brief History of Both Systems</h2>

    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background: #f1f5f9;">
          <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: left;">Year</th>
          <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: left;">Event</th>
          <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: left;">System</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">1913</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin Fuhao created by the Commission on the Unification of Pronunciation</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Bopomofo</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">1918</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Officially adopted by the Republic of China government</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Bopomofo</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">1949</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">PRC government begins work on a new romanization system</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">1958</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Hanyu Pinyin officially adopted in mainland China</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">1982</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin becomes ISO 7098 international standard</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">2009</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Taiwan adopts Pinyin for romanization of street signs (but keeps Zhuyin for education)</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Both</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Today</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin dominant internationally; Zhuyin dominant in Taiwan domestic use</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Both</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <!-- Side-by-Side -->
    <h2 id="side-by-side">Side-by-Side Symbol Comparison</h2>

    <p>Here is how the two systems map to the same sounds. This table covers the most common initials and finals:</p>

    <h3>Initials (Consonants)</h3>
    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background: #f1f5f9;">
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">b</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄅ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">p</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄆ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">m</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄇ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">f</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄈ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">d</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄉ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">t</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄊ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">n</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄋ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">l</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄌ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">g</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄍ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">k</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄎ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">h</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄏ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">j</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄐ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">q</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄑ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">x</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄒ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">zh</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄓ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ch</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄔ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">sh</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄕ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">r</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄖ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">z</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄗ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">c</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄘ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">s</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄙ</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Finals (Vowels)</h3>
    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background: #f1f5f9;">
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">a</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄚ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">o</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄛ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">e</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄜ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ai</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄞ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ei</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄟ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ao</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄠ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ou</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄡ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">an</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄢ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">en</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄣ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ang</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄤ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">eng</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄥ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">er</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄦ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">i</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄧ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">u</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄨ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ü</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ㄩ</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Tones</h3>
    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background: #f1f5f9;">
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Tone</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Pinyin Mark</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Zhuyin Mark</th>
          <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Tone 1 (flat)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ā</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">(no mark)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">mā = ㄇㄚ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Tone 2 (rising)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">á</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ˊ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">má = ㄇㄚˊ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Tone 3 (dip)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ǎ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ˇ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">mǎ = ㄇㄚˇ</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Tone 4 (falling)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">à</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ˋ</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">mà = ㄇㄚˋ</td></tr>
        <tr><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Neutral tone</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ma (no mark)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">˙ (dot before)</td><td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">ma = ˙ㄇㄚ</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <!-- Pinyin Pros/Cons -->
    <h2 id="pinyin-pros-cons">Pinyin: Advantages and Disadvantages</h2>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.2rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem;">
        <strong style="color: #16a34a; font-size: 1.1rem;">✅ Advantages</strong>
        <ul style="margin: 0.8rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.92rem;">
          <li><strong>Instant readability</strong> — Uses letters you already know (A-Z)</li>
          <li><strong>Universal resources</strong> — Almost all textbooks, apps, and dictionaries use Pinyin</li>
          <li><strong>HSK standard</strong> — Required for the most recognized Chinese proficiency test</li>
          <li><strong>Technology support</strong> — Default input on all platforms (iOS, Android, Windows, Mac)</li>
          <li><strong>International recognition</strong> — ISO standard, used in passports and maps</li>
          <li><strong>Quick to learn</strong> — If you read English, you can start using Pinyin in hours</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div style="background: #fef2f2; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem;">
        <strong style="color: #dc2626; font-size: 1.1rem;">❌ Disadvantages</strong>
        <ul style="margin: 0.8rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.92rem;">
          <li><strong>English interference</strong> — You will mispronounce "q", "x", "c", "r" based on English habits</li>
          <li><strong>Crutch dependency</strong> — Some learners never move beyond Pinyin to reading characters</li>
          <li><strong>Misleading spellings</strong> — "shi" looks like English but sounds nothing like it</li>
          <li><strong>Tone neglect</strong> — Easy to mentally skip tone marks when reading familiar letters</li>
          <li><strong>Not used in Taiwan classrooms</strong> — Limited usefulness for Taiwan-based study</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Bopomofo Pros/Cons -->
    <h2 id="bopomofo-pros-cons">Bopomofo: Advantages and Disadvantages</h2>

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1.2rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem;">
        <strong style="color: #16a34a; font-size: 1.1rem;">✅ Advantages</strong>
        <ul style="margin: 0.8rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.92rem;">
          <li><strong>No English interference</strong> — ㄑ does not remind you of English "q" at all</li>
          <li><strong>Better pronunciation</strong> — Forces you to learn each sound as a brand-new symbol</li>
          <li><strong>Taiwan integration</strong> — Essential for living, studying, or working in Taiwan</li>
          <li><strong>Children's materials</strong> — Access to phonetic-annotated Taiwanese children's books</li>
          <li><strong>Faster character learning</strong> — No Pinyin crutch means you connect sounds to characters faster</li>
          <li><strong>Cultural immersion</strong> — Shows commitment to Taiwanese language partners and teachers</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div style="background: #fef2f2; border-radius: 10px; padding: 1.2rem;">
        <strong style="color: #dc2626; font-size: 1.1rem;">❌ Disadvantages</strong>
        <ul style="margin: 0.8rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.92rem;">
          <li><strong>New symbols to memorize</strong> — 37 symbols + 4 tone marks to learn from scratch</li>
          <li><strong>Limited resources</strong> — Few international textbooks or apps use Zhuyin</li>
          <li><strong>Not recognized internationally</strong> — Cannot be used for romanization in academic papers</li>
          <li><strong>Slower start</strong> — Takes 1-2 weeks just to read the symbols comfortably</li>
          <li><strong>No HSK support</strong> — Cannot use Zhuyin in Chinese proficiency exams</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Decision Guide -->
    <h2 id="decision-guide">Which Should You Learn? Decision Guide</h2>

    <p>Your choice depends on your specific situation. Use this decision table:</p>

    <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <thead>
        <tr style="background: #f1f5f9;">
          <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: left;">Your Situation</th>
          <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: center;">Recommended</th>
          <th style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: left;">Why</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Self-studying with apps and online resources</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: center; font-weight: bold; color: #2563eb;">Pinyin</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Almost all apps (Duolingo, HelloChinese, Pleco) use Pinyin</td></tr>
        <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">Preparing for HSK exams</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: center; font-weight: bold; color: #2563eb;">Pinyin</td><td style="padding: 10px; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;">HSK uses Pinyin exclusively</td></tr>
